{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18077"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18077"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78853"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10791"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5680"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78853"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA group of medical students are discussing interesting cases they have seen during their clinical rotations while having lunch in the hospital cafeteria. Though they do not mention patient names, they describe unique clinical presentations and management details that could potentially identify specific patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes why this situation represents a breach of patient privacy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Students are not qualified healthcare providers","Cases are discussed without educational purpose","Discussion occurs outside formal teaching sessions","Patient information is shared in a public space","Patients have not consented to case discussions"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary privacy breach in this scenario is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epatient information is shared in a public space\u003C/strong\u003E. Even without using names, discussing identifiable patient details in areas where others can overhear violates patient confidentiality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudents are not qualified healthcare providers\u003C/strong\u003E - Medical students are considered part of the healthcare team and are permitted to discuss cases appropriately for learning purposes when in suitable settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECases are discussed without educational purpose\u003C/strong\u003E - The educational merit of the discussion is not the central concern, as the primary issue relates to the inappropriate public setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscussion occurs outside formal teaching sessions\u003C/strong\u003E - Case discussions may occur in informal settings provided they take place in appropriate private locations where confidentiality can be maintained.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatients have not consented to case discussions\u003C/strong\u003E - While explicit consent is not typically required for educational case discussions, these conversations must occur in appropriate private settings regardless of consent status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers have an ethical and legal obligation to protect patient privacy. Discussions about patients should only occur in private settings where confidentiality can be maintained, such as conference rooms, offices, or designated teaching spaces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers must maintain patient confidentiality by not discussing patient information in public spaces.","Breaches of privacy can occur through casual conversations about patients, even when names are not mentioned.","Patient information should only be shared with those directly involved in their care on a need-to-know basis."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18077"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T21:47:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T21:47:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10791"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78853"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"